### 2. `force-dynamic` on Every Single Page — Zero Caching

**File(s):** [`page.tsx`](file:///f:/PROJECTS/wayfindsolutions/src/app/page.tsx), [`services/page.tsx`](file:///f:/PROJECTS/wayfindsolutions/src/app/services/page.tsx), [`blog/page.tsx`](file:///f:/PROJECTS/wayfindsolutions/src/app/blog/page.tsx), [`work/page.tsx`](file:///f:/PROJECTS/wayfindsolutions/src/app/work/page.tsx), [`careers/page.tsx`](file:///f:/PROJECTS/wayfindsolutions/src/app/careers/page.tsx), [`start-project/page.tsx`](file:///f:/PROJECTS/wayfindsolutions/src/app/start-project/page.tsx)

```ts
export const dynamic = "force-dynamic"; // ← on EVERY public page
```

**What's happening:** Every single visitor to every public page triggers a live query to Supabase Tokyo. With a shared micro-instance, this is expensive. Data like blog posts, services, and team members **almost never changes** yet is fetched fresh from a cross-continent database on every request.

**Impact:** Each load adds 80–300ms database RTT + Supabase shared compute latency. With auto-pause also in play, this compounds to seconds.

**Fix:** Use ISR (Incremental Static Regeneration) for all public pages:

```ts
// Remove: export const dynamic = "force-dynamic";
// Add instead:
export const revalidate = 3600; // re-fetch from DB at most once per hour

// For pages that almost never change (about, careers):
export const revalidate = 86400; // once per day
```

Only `/admin` layout legitimately needs `force-dynamic`.

